<TEI xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0" xmlns:frus="http://history.state.gov/frus/ns/1.0">
    <teiHeader><fileDesc><titleStmt><title>No. 43 
                    
                        Marshal Stalin to Prime
                        Minister Churchill
                    
                    Printed from a copy of a courtesy copy received by
                        the American Embassy at Moscow on June 1.</title></titleStmt><sourceDesc><bibl type="frus-volume-id">frus1945Berlinv01</bibl><bibl type="frus-document-id">d43</bibl><bibl type="frus-document-number">43</bibl><bibl type="frus-div-subtype">historical-document</bibl></sourceDesc></fileDesc><profileDesc><settingDesc><setting><date notBefore="1945-05-30T00:00:00-05:00" notAfter="1945-05-30T23:59:59-05:00"/></setting></settingDesc></profileDesc></teiHeader><text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1945-05-30T23:59:59-05:00" frus:doc-dateTime-min="1945-05-30T00:00:00-05:00" n="43" subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d43">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">740.00119 Potsdam/6–645</note>
                <head>No. 43 <lb/>
                    <hi rend="italic">
                        <persName corresp="#p_SMIV2" type="from">Marshal Stalin</persName> to Prime
                        Minister <persName corresp="#p_CMWS1" type="to">Churchill</persName>
                    </hi>
                    <note n="1" xml:id="d43fn1">Printed from a copy of a courtesy copy received by
                        the American Embassy at Moscow on June 1.</note>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <seg rendition="#center">[Translation?]</seg>
                </opener>
                <opener>
                    <seg rendition="#left">
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">top secret</hi>
                    </seg>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">[<placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Moscow</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1945-05-30">May 30,
                            1945</date>.<note n="2" xml:id="d43fn2">So dated in <persName corresp="#p_CMWS1">Churchill</persName>, <hi rend="italic">Triumph
                                and Tragedy</hi>, p. 581, and in <hi rend="italic">
                                <persName corresp="#p_SMIV2">Stalin</persName>’s
                            Correspondence</hi>, vol. <hi rend="smallcaps">i</hi>, p.
                        362.</note>]</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>For Prime Minister <persName corresp="#p_CMWS1">Churchill</persName> from
                        <persName corresp="#p_SMIV2">Stalin</persName>:</p>
                <p>I have received your message of May 29th.<note n="3" xml:id="d43fn3">See <ref target="#d39">document No. 39</ref>.</note> A few hours after I had
                    received it Mr. <persName corresp="#p_HHL1">Hopkins</persName> was with me and
                    told me that President <pb facs="0221" n="89" xml:id="pg_89"/>
                    <persName corresp="#p_THS1">Truman</persName> thinks the most convenient date
                    for a meeting of the three would be June 15th.<note n="4" xml:id="d43fn4">
                        <p>The following note by <persName corresp="#p_BCE2">Charles E.
                                Bohlen</persName>, dated June 1, is typed on the source copy: <quote rend="blockquote">
                                <p>“I called Mr. <persName corresp="#p_PVN1">Pavlov</persName> to
                                    verify the question of the date of the meeting. He confirmed
                                    that both <persName corresp="#p_SMIV2">Marshal Stalin</persName>
                                    and Mr. <persName corresp="#p_MVM1">Molotov</persName> and
                                    himself had clearly understood that the President desired it
                                    around the middle of July.</p>
                                <p>“After verifying the text of <persName corresp="#p_SMIV2">Marshal
                                        Stalin</persName>’s message to Mr. <persName corresp="#p_CMWS1">Churchill</persName>, Mr. <persName corresp="#p_PVN1">Pavlov</persName> telephoned back to say
                                    that in the original there was no mistake and the date had been
                                    clearly written July 15th and not repeat not June.”</p>
                            </quote>
                        </p>
                        <p>The correct date was in the message as received by <persName corresp="#p_CMWS1">Churchill</persName>. See <persName corresp="#p_CMWS1">Churchill</persName>, <hi rend="italic">Triumph
                                and Tragedy</hi>, p. 581.</p>
                    </note> I have no objection to that date if you also agree to it.</p>
                <p>I send you my best wishes.</p>
            </div>
        </body>
    </text>
